New Hope in India
Cambridge, U.S.—India's latest elections may be the most significant positive economic event of 2014.
Indian voters decisively rejected the Indian National Congress, which had ruled the country almost continuously since its independence from Britain in 1947.
They might be happy about this decision.
Sonia Gandhi, the widow of former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi and leader of the Indian National Congress, has been effectively ruling from behind the scenes since 1998, while Prime Minister Singh is merely a puppet.
Under her leadership, the Congress Party pursued a populist agenda, increasing transfer payments, which led to India's annual economic growth rate falling below 4% in 2013.
Per capita GDP remains around $4,000, less than half of China's.
The newly elected Prime Minister Narendra Modi pledged during his campaign to bring rapid growth in employment and income across all of India, similar to what he achieved as Chief Minister of Gujarat.
Under Modi's leadership, Gujarat has become a business-friendly state, expanding economic activities and attracting commercial investments from both within and outside India.
An important feature of the latest election is that Modi's Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) has secured an absolute majority in the Lok Sabha, which can be considered a historic achievement in India.
Therefore, Modi does not need to compromise with other national or regional parties in order to pursue his legislative agenda.
Two key officials will lend a hand to Modi on the economic plan.
Newly appointed Finance Minister Arun Jaitley has extensive political experience and previously held ministerial positions in the preceding BJP government.
Jeter is also renowned as a strategic thinker who shows sympathy toward commercial interests.
Raghuram Rajan will continue to serve as Governor of the Reserve Bank of India (the central bank). A distinguished economist, Rajan has demonstrated a desire to reduce India's double-digit annual inflation rate during his tenure as Governor, and has attempted to reform some of the inherent productivity constraints in India's financial sector.
The measures needed to stimulate economic growth will take time to be implemented and to yield results.
But if you want to know whether the new government is taking action to achieve faster long-term growth, you should examine whether progress has been made in the following ten policy areas.
Education.
Although India has outstanding higher education and technical institutions, only a small portion of the population can access the opportunities they offer, due to the underdeveloped primary and secondary education system in the country.
Only 60% of Indian adults have literacy skills at the primary school level.
The teachers themselves have poor educational backgrounds and lack motivation; many teachers never even show up at the schools where they are supposed to teach.
Infrastructure.
India needs better roads and ports to efficiently transport products across the country and around the world.
The recent expansion of private airlines and airports indicates that private enterprises can also play a significant role in this field.
Financial Integration.
Large budget deficits absorb national savings that could otherwise be used to expand business investment. Budget deficits lead to an increase in national debt that can only be financed through future taxes.
Privatization.
The government-owned manufacturing and other industry enterprises in India operate inefficiently, often resulting in the depletion of national savings.
Selling these enterprises directly helps accelerate economic growth.
Cancel subsidies.
Power and energy subsidies have led to wasteful overconsumption and increased fiscal deficits.
Although these subsidies are politically difficult to eliminate, they should be replaced with cash transfers. Currently, India has a relatively efficient cash transfer system, thanks to a new fingerprint-based cash transfer initiative that has attracted significant attention.
Agricultural reform.
Under the current system, the government purchases, stores, and distributes agricultural products.
The result was a large accumulation of goods in warehouses, while production incentives were misdirected.
The agricultural market should be privatized.
Property rights and territorial demarcation.
If you have ever been to Mumbai or any other major Indian city, you will see how zoning restrictions lead to inefficient land use in urban areas, hindering the process of desalination.
Unclear property rights, especially those of agricultural land, have hindered industrialization in rural areas.
Ease foreign investment restrictions.
Currently, foreign companies cannot become controlling shareholders of banks and insurance companies.
Easing these restrictions can strengthen the financial sector and play an important role in economic growth.
Tax reform.
India's complex state and central sales tax system distorts domestic trade.
The debate over replacing these taxes with a national value-added tax and implementing a shared tax system has been ongoing for a long time and now should move into the implementation phase.
Corruption.
High-level corruption cases have undermined economic confidence and hindered officials' decision-making.
India is also deeply troubled by small-scale corruption, with bribery having become a common feature in all business and personal transactions.
The government should severely punish high-level corruption and restrict small-scale corruption through a new cash transfer system.
Driven by expectations of stronger growth and increased profits, India's stock market has risen by 20% this year.
Now, Modi and the BJP need to prove to the world that they can fulfill their election promises.
